prediction markets are a proven method to make predictions and decisions that can reliably perform as well or better than any other known decision method such as experts, seniority, voting, dictatorship, debate, surveys, etc.

a prediction market is like a stock in the stock market. anyone can buy and sell shares in it. the market's value changes based only on the activity of buyers and sellers. prediction markets are unlike stock markets in that a stock market has one stock for one company, while prediction markets have many markets for one comapny. an individual prediction market represents a prediction about a specific, answerable question. the question must currently not have an answer, but we must be able to answer the question soon. we can use prediction markets to predict many things per company, and make decisions based on the predictions. the predictions will be as good or better than any other method, so the decisions based on them will be the best achievable decisions given the information available at that time.

for example, imagine we operate a retail store and we want to know, will it rain tomorrow? if it will rain, our store should display more umbrellas. if it will not rain, we should display more sunglasses. we open a prediction market. the question of the prediction market is, will it rain tomorrow? in our rain tomorrow prediction market, anyone can buy yes and no shares, until the time comes when we need to decide and act on our prediction. when its time to act, we close the market and prepare the store for the next day based on everyones predictions. the next day, it either rains or it doesnt and we learn the answer to the question, did it rain today? we resolve the market and pay the winners. this is different from a stock, because the prediction market closes and resolves instead of staying open. a prediction market is different from voting, because there is an objective answer to the question and the winners are not the majority, the winners are the participants that made correct predictions. what if no one wants to bet in a market? you can subsidize a market with an ante that contributes to the payout and attracts participants, pay for information.

prediction markets let you make better decisions than other decision methods because they allow anyone to participate and the markets pay participants for making accurate predictions. the incentive of a prediction market is to be accurate, unlike other methods. a prediction market allows people to put their money where their mouth is and incentivize people who know better. if they are right then they will be paid for contributing to an accurate prediction that can then be applied to make a useful decision. if they are wrong they will lose money to pay people who are right. over time, people who are wrong will either run out of money or learn from their errors to improve their predictions until they become right.

